1 Data

1.1 Seattle Incident-Based Reporting

Below are maps which show the spatial locations of all SPD incidents in 2016 for which data is available. The full data set is available here. Each map corresponds to one of the Uniform Crime Reporting (UCR)s 12 categories while the colored areas delineate one of SPDs 17 police sectors.

1.2 National Incident-Based Reporting

Unfortunately, the data presented above do not include any demographic information; this is obviously problematic when one is interested in examining crime data along racial dimensions. Fortunately, SPD participates in the National Incident-Based Reporting System (NIBRS) and some of the records approximately 40% submitted into this system do contain demographic information.

These data are matched the spatial data above by incident datetime and type of crime which only works for instances in which this information is unique (otherwise it is not possible to match). Using this strategy, approximately 14% of the records can be matched. The signficance of this is that the matched data provide demographic information by both sector AND race.

Aggregrate counts are summarized below:

where: A indicates Asian, B indicates Black, H indicates Hispanic, I indicates Alaska Native or American Indian, and W indicates White. The solid portion of each bar in the plot above represents data found in the Arrestee segment of the NIBRS data set while the transparent portion represents data found in the Offender segment of the data set.

SPDs Terry stop data can be found here. The aggregated demographic information is summarized below:

where A, B, H, I, and W are defined as above. In this case, the solid portion of each bar represents stops that led to an arrest while the transparent portion represents stops that did not.

1.4 American Community Survey

Demographic data for each police sector are obtained by utilizing the 2015 five-year estimates of the American Community Survey. These data are available at the block-group level of which the city contains 482; of these, 389 lie completely within one of the the 17 police sectors. For those block-groups lying in multiple sectors, the percentage of area of overlap bewteen the sector and the block-group is used to spatially allocate the data. For example, approximatley 30% of the area of Block Group 6 of Census Tract 32 is located in sector B and so sector B is apportioned 30% of that block-groups population, etc.

A natural point of comparison is the deomgraphic profile of the city as a whole. This is summarized below:

2 Models

For each race \(r = \{A, B, I, W\}\) and sector \(s\), the annual number of Terry stops \(y_{rs}\) is modeled as an overdispersed Poisson regression using the rate of crimes \(\theta_{rs}\) as an offset:

\[\begin{equation*} y_{rst} \sim \text{Poisson} \left( \theta_{rs} e^{\mu + \alpha_r + \beta_s + \epsilon_{rst}} \right) \end{equation*}\]

where the \(\alpha_r\)s control for each race, the \(\beta_s\)s account for variation between sectors, and the \(\epsilon_{rs}\)s allow for overdispersion. The subscript \(t\) is used explicitly since two years of data is available for use. Of course, \(\theta_{rs}\) is not observed. Thus, the number of previous years arrests \(a_{rs(t-1)}\) is used as a proxy:

\[\begin{equation} y_{rst} \sim \text{Poisson} \left( a_{rs(t-1)} e^{\mu + \alpha_r + \beta_s + \epsilon_{rst}} \right) \tag{2.1} \end{equation}\]

In addition, two alternative specifications are considered. First, the offset \(a_{rs(t-1)}\) is modeled more flexibly by including it as a predictor with its own coefficent:

\[\begin{equation} y_{rst} \sim \text{Poisson} \left( e^{\gamma \log(a_{rs(t-1)}) + \mu + \alpha_r + \beta_s + \epsilon_{rst}} \right) \tag{2.2} \end{equation}\]

Second, the proportion of the sectors population that is black \(z_{1s}\) is added as a predictor:

\[\begin{equation} y_{rst} \sim \text{Poisson} \left( a_{rs(t-1)} e^{\mu + \alpha_r + \beta_s + \rho z_{1s} + \epsilon_{rst}} \right) \tag{2.3} \end{equation}\]

As alternative approach, the number of arrests \(a_{rst}\) are assumed to be a realization of the true crime rate:

\[\begin{equation*} \begin{split} y_{rst} &\sim \text{Poisson} \left( \theta_{rs} e^{\mu + \alpha_r + \beta_s + \epsilon_{rst}} \right) \\ a_{rst} &\sim \text{Poisson} \left( \theta_{rs} \right) \end{split} \end{equation*}\]

with the rate then modeled as function of each races population in the sector \(p_{rs}\) and an additional set of race and sector parameters \(\delta_r\) and \(\zeta_s\):

\[\begin{equation} \log(\theta_{rs}) = \log(p_{rs}) + \nu + \delta_r + \zeta_s + \upsilon_{rs} \tag{2.4} \end{equation}\]

Two additional specifications of the model for \(\theta_{rs}\) are also considered. First, the population \(p_{rs}\) is given its own coefficent:

\[\begin{equation} \log(\theta_{rs}) = \gamma \log(p_{rs}) + \nu + \delta_r + \zeta_s + \upsilon_{rs} \tag{2.5} \end{equation}\]

Second, each sectors log median income \(z_{2s}\) and proportion of the population with at least a four-year degree \(z_{3s}\) are included as predictors:

\[\begin{equation} \log(\theta_{rs}) = \log(p_{rs}) + \nu + \delta_r + \zeta_s + \phi z_{2s} + \psi z_{3s} + \upsilon_{rs} \tag{2.6} \end{equation}\]

As a final approach, a model is considered where overdispersion in the model for \(a_{rst}\) is allowed for:

\[\begin{equation*} \begin{split} y_{rst} &\sim \text{Poisson} \left( \theta_{rs} e^{\mu + \alpha_r + \beta_s + \epsilon_{rst}} \right) \\ a_{rst} &\sim \text{Poisson} \left( \theta_{rs} e^{\omega_{rst}} \right) \end{split} \end{equation*}\]

Similar specifications for the true crime rate as in (2.4), (2.5), and (2.6) are used with the exception of the \(\upsilon_{rs}\) term.

The models are fit using \(\texttt{Stan}\) with the following normal priors:

\[\begin{equation*} \begin{split} \alpha_r &\sim N(0, \sigma_{\alpha}^2) \\ \beta_s &\sim N(0, \sigma_{\beta}^2) \\ \epsilon_{rs} &\sim N(0, \sigma_{\epsilon}^2) \end{split} \end{equation*}\]

where \(\sigma_{\alpha}\), \(\sigma_{\beta}\), and \(\sigma_{\epsilon}\) represent the variation in the parameters for race, sector, and overdispersion respectively. A similar set of priors are used for the approahces which explicitly model \(\theta_{rs}\):

\[\begin{equation*} \begin{split} \delta_r &\sim N(0, \sigma_{\delta}^2) \\ \zeta_s &\sim N(0, \sigma_{\zeta}^2) \\ \upsilon_{rs} &\sim N(0, \sigma_{\upsilon}^2) \\ \omega_{rs} &\sim N(0, \sigma_{\omega}^2) \end{split} \end{equation*}\]

The above \(\sigma\) parameters as well as all other parameters in each of the models are given flat priors.
